<br>
That's a great quote by Sterling M. McMurrin.<br>
<br>
The idea that we are a cosmic accident and not a divine plan is painful, the thought that this is it, this is all there is, is troubling, even to an atheist like myself.<br>
<br>
I would like to believe and I do think about it quite a bit.  As I approach the age of 33 (the age Jesus died) I think a lot more about my own mortality, I'm getting my first gray hairs and the knowledge that I'm not going to get a magic &quot;Get out of Death Free&quot; card is really starting to sink in.<br>
<br>
The cynical part of me says this is where religion came from in the first place, the deap seated fear of death, the fear of our precious, unique self ceasing to exist.  Humans couldn't face that fear and so, religion was born.  If you live a good life, you go to heaven and live forever in paradise, that sounds pretty good.<br>
<br>
A lot better than the alternative: you die and your body rots and becomes food for plants and that is your purpose, to keep the planet life cycle humming along.  <br>
<br>
I would like to believe. <p><a href="http://www.saraquael.com/gloriana.html"><img src="http://fyd.fuxored.net/glorymedium.jpg" border="0"></a><p>
