quot; either, but this is true.)<br>
<br>
I'm hardcore into science, I was a dual chem/bio major when I was a premed student.  The more I learned about science, the more I believed in a 'creator'.  There is entirely too much that works exactly right for it to be circumstance.  Quick example is H20.  As you cool a substance, the molecules get closer together and then change states.  So going from a liquid to a solid makes the substance denser.  Yep, it's smaller cause the same mass is packed closer together.  EXCEPT for water.  Why do your pipes burst?  Because water actually breaks all the rules and expands when you freeze it.  Perhaps have something to do with all the life that continues to exist when the waterways freeze over?  The ice is at the top (at 32 degrees, which keeps the much colder air away from the water).  Pure coincidence that the substance that breaks the &quot;rules&quot; is the one that needs to in order to promote life?  Just something to think about.<br>
<br>
I wouldn't try to push my religeous views on anyone, that's a decision everyone must make within themselves.  I had a lack of belief when I was younger, but have seen too many things to make me change my mind. Honest to God (hope no one takes me to court over that) miracles even.  <br>
<br>
